reviews.name: DEBAJIT BANERJEE
reviews.text: Tagore Park is at Light House Hill Road, Hampankatta. St. Aloysius Chapel and City Centre Mall are nearby. It is a famous attraction due to the Light House on the top of Bavuta Gudde/Flag Hill. 50 ft. high Light House was built in 1890. It was a beautiful attraction but currently not maintained at all. Not sure about the reason - may be COVID-19. There is no entrance fee but it is completely closed now.

reviews.text: A hidden Gem in centre of the city. Good place to visit for persons who like museums and old stuff. Easily can spend an hour and more if you are interested. Ticket costs Rs 20 per head. Parking can be done outside premises also.  Parking inside premises also available, but it is mentioned as paid parking on board. Historical collections containing statues, paintings, wooden works, idols, pictures and others. Well maintained. Neat. No crowd was there. The garden could be improved if number of visitors are more. School kids must be shown this place.

reviews.name: 58 Calvin Dsilva
reviews.text:
The Shreemanthi Bhai Memorial government museum Bijai, Mangalore , has a great collection of antiques, stone age tools, manuscripts paintings etc.
I must say that the museum has see great improvement over the years.
The authorities have Renovated the building without  altering the buildings Italian design.
One could spend their leisure time , appreciating the  cannons , toys , trunks and statues.
They do have an art gallery that displays paintings in a well lit room.
# Criticism :-
* There is a sign board on the main road that directs visitors to the museum. The board has lost its lustre over time.
It needs urgent revamping.
* I found the artifacts kept outside were neglected. Exposed to the elements of nature.
Which I felt was unwise.
*According to the museum Brochure the entrance fees for adults is 2₹.
However the museum charges 20 ₹.
This needs to be corrected.

Summary.
The museum has seen great improvement over the years.
The curator of the museum was really friendly and supportive. They do encourage school tours .
I truly believe that the citizens are missing out on a treasure trove by not visiting out museum.
Get lost in the beauty of the museum.
Give it a shot. #crushit

reviews.name: Ganesh Kalyanpurkar
reviews.text: Good place to visit once in mangalore City if you have intrest in historical and ancient collection.

reviews.name: alan fernandes
reviews.text:
Museum was inaugrated in 1960 by shri. B. D. Jatti, the then chief minister of karnataka.The major portion of collections was made by col. V.R Mirajkar.The museum was his living house designed and constructed In nearly same blueprint of glorious structures of Milan, Italy in 1935. Later it was donated to the karnataka government. The museum is named in honor and memory of his beloved mother Sreemanthi Bhai.
The museum consists of Paleolithic & Neolithic stone tools, coins, metal utensils, ethnologixal materials, arms & armors,replicas of Harappa and Mohenjodaro, Gandhara & Takshahshila school of art, Warangal, Nagarajunakonda, Sarnath, Konark, Kushana, Ahimchatra etc. Animal seals, wooden panels, gigantic wooden figurines, porcelain materials, musical instruments, lamps, clock,wooden god figurines and other antiques.
The first floor of the building is dedicated to collections made by col.V.R. Mirajkar. It also contains a photo gallery, Gandhiji photo gallery and a kids section. Outer premises covers hero stone, sati stones, kannada inscriptions, statues, of soldiers, Jaina, Veerabhadra, Vinayaka, Nagastones & cannons collected from Jamalabad Fort, Belthangady.
It is open from 10 am to 5:30 pm from Tuesday to Sunday. Second Saturday & govt holidays, museum is closed. Monday weekly off.
Entry fee is rs. 20.
(This review is compiled from the museum pamphlet)

reviews.name: Wilson Paul Libera
reviews.text:
This is a water themed amusement park near Mangalore. It is almost 12 kilometres away from Mangalore city. The entrance fees for an adult is ₹350/-. I think the entrance fee is too high for the facilities available inside the park.

There are only 2 big pools in the park. One family pool and one pool into which the water rides take you. Of these, you can only enjoy in the family pool as the lifeguards will not let you stay in the other pool. Both the pools are not deep enough for adults(maximum 3 feet deep). There is no wave pool.

There are only 7 water rides available in the park. Nothing else. No mechanical rides. So you will end up going in the same rides again and again.

You are not supposed to bring food from outside. You will have to be happy with what they serve at prices that are a bit high in the canteen within the premises.

They charge you for lockers. Daily rent of ₹ 50/- for small ones and ₹ 100 for bigger ones. Swimming costumes and accessories available for rent and purchase there. The changing rooms and washrooms are clean enough.

I visited the park on a Sunday. Even then, the park was not that crowded and was able to spent some great time with my friends.

The park will open at 10:30 am and close at 5:00 pm.

reviews.text: Excellent water park in Mangalore. Timing is from 10:30am to 5pm. There is hotel inside,but it is too costly. You are not allowed to go outside. Its a very cool place to spend weekends. It has good security.

reviews.name: Manish Garg
reviews.text: Great place for kids outing for entire day within city limits. They have a big zoo, lake with boating facility and big science park. My kids loved the planetarium, I would recommend it as must visit, internal dome shaped theatre is amazing and gives u feel of 3D without any glasses. Science centre is also fun with number of experiments for kids to enjoy. It will take almost entire day, we reached at 11 and left at 6:30. There are plenty of snacks plazas inside.

reviews.name: Shankarnag Basavaraju
reviews.text:
Excellent day out picnic spot located in the outskirts of Mangalore city.
As in the name 'Nisargadhama' in Kannada means Brahmanda meaning the Universe it is a mini universe with so many attractions ranging from Planetarium to old heritage house Gutthumane located in vast green surrounding.
First to start with you have ample of free parking space for both two and four wheelers. There is a seperate restrooms for both men and women in the parking lot.
Then comes the entry point where one has to purchase entry tickets. One can purchase for specific categories or combo for all entries. The rates are nominal.
One can walk around or can take service of electric vehicles by paying nominal fare to get day pass to ferry between the places.
The attractions include
1) Swami Vivekananda Planetarium - Both Kannada and English shows
2) Science centre - Like Sir M Vishweswaraiah museum in Bengaluru
3) Zoo - Very good with most of animals and birds placed in natural habitat
4) Lake Garden - Wonderful garden around lake with walking path and resting benches. The peddle boat and machine boating service is available
5) Artisan and Gutthumane - Like pottery, blacksmith, Beaten rice or Avalakki making and collection of old items and traditional dance makeup and dresses like Yakshagana
6) Botonical Museum
In addition, Manasa amusement park is there attached to it and big restaurant both closed due to Covid 19.
All the places were well maintained neat and clean with very good roads and pavement or footpaths, resting benches.
Every where there is clean RO drinking water facilities in addition to separate free washrooms for gents and ladies.
The place is open from morning 9.30 to evening 5.30.
